SIMPLE: undress
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Undress
<hw>Un*dress"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[1st pref.
<ets>un-</ets> + <ets>dress</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To divest of clothes; to strip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divest of ornaments to disrobe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To take the dressing, or covering,
from; <as>as, to <ex>undress</ex> a wound</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Undress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Undress
<hw>Un"dress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A loose,
negligent dress; ordinary dress, as distinguished from <xex>full
dress</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil. & Naval)</fld> <def>An authorized habitual
dress of officers and soldiers, but not full-dress uniform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Undress parade</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a
substitute for dress parade, allowed in bad weather, the companies
forming without arms, and the ceremony being shortened.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Undubitable</ent>⟦br⟧
